# KINETIC_GOVERNANCE: Memory-Safe Ingestion & Execution Boundary

**Classification:** Project Ebony / Cyber-Resilience Layer  
**Target Architecture:** no_std Rust / Borrow Checker / DMA Ring Buffers / Zero-Copy FlatBuffers  

This specification handles the strictly memory-safe ingestion of untrusted external data (Sub-GHz radio frames, NMEA weather strings, I/Q radar basebands). Traditional kinetic operating systems rely on C/C++ for hardware-level speed, leaving them fatally exposed to buffer overflows, use-after-free exploits, and pointer arithmetic errors. To guarantee physical sovereignty, the edge node must parse adversarial data at microsecond speeds without ever allowing memory corruption. The ingestion boundary is written entirely in `no_std` Rust, utilizing compile-time memory guarantees to mathematically eliminate Remote Code Execution (RCE) vectors.

## Nomenclature & Acronym Glossary

| Term | Definition | Context |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Borrow Checker** | Rust Compiler Feature | Mathematically guarantees memory safety by ensuring data references do not outlive the data they point to, preventing dangling pointers. |
| **no_std** | Rust Attribute | Compiles the code without the standard OS library or dynamic heap allocator, forcing bare-metal execution. |
| **RCE** | Remote Code Execution | A fatal cyber-attack where an adversary exploits a memory flaw to execute arbitrary commands on the target hardware. |
| **Zero-Cost Abstraction** | Design Principle | High-level programming constructs that compile down to machine code just as fast as hand-written C. |

