## 1. Mathematical Elimination of Memory Exploits
The perimeter cannot trust the data it receives. Every byte pulled from the airwaves must be treated as a weaponized exploit attempt.

* **Compile-Time Spatial Safety:** The `no_std` Rust compiler natively injects bounds-checking into all array and slice accesses. If a FlatBuffer parser attempts to read byte 257 of a 256-byte DMA buffer, the kernel executes an immediate, safe panic rather than overwriting the adjacent instruction pointer.
* **Deterministic Lifetimes:** The borrow checker enforces absolute data ownership. When a raw DMA packet is passed to the cryptographic verification engine, the compiler mathematically guarantees that no other concurrent thread can mutate or read that memory space until the verification block yields control. This entirely eliminates data-race conditions in the multi-core kinetic RT-PREEMPT loop.

---

## 2. Zero-Copy DMA Ring Buffers
Memory safety cannot come at the cost of execution speed. If the ingestion loop is safe but slow, the physical asset crashes.

* **Static Memory Pre-Allocation:** Because dynamic memory allocation (malloc/heap) introduces non-deterministic latency and fragmentation, the Rust environment is entirely heapless. All DMA ring buffers are statically allocated in the `.bss` segment during compilation.
* **In-Place FlatBuffer Parsing:** As data is ingested into the static Rust slice, the FlatBuffer schema overlays a strictly typed struct directly onto the raw bytes. The CPU does not execute a single memory copy operation. It validates the cryptographic signature and reads the telemetry natively from the DMA register memory, achieving C-level execution speed with mathematically proven memory safety.

---

## 3. The Raw Code: Memory-Safe DMA Ingestion
This is the new bare-metal reality of cyber-resilient parsing. The kernel pulls the untrusted packet from the hardware, verifies the slice bounds at compile-time, and extracts the payload with absolute memory safety.

```rust
#![no_std]

use core::panic::PanicInfo;
use ebony_hal::dma::{DmaRingBuffer, BufferError};
use ebony_hal::mesh::FlatBufferPayload;
use ebony_hal::crypto::PufHardware;

// Statically allocated, heapless DMA ring buffer
static mut RX_RING_BUFFER: DmaRingBuffer<1024> = DmaRingBuffer::new();

// RT-PREEMPT Secure Ingestion Boundary (Pure no_std Rust)
pub fn ingest_untrusted_mesh_frame() -> Result<FlatBufferPayload, BufferError> {
    
    // 1. Safe Abstraction over Mutable Statics
    // The borrow checker ensures this static buffer cannot be accessed concurrently by other threads
    let buffer = unsafe { &mut RX_RING_BUFFER };

    // 2. Deterministic, Bounds-Checked DMA Read
    if let Ok(frame_slice) = buffer.read_next_frame() {
        
        // frame_slice is a mathematically bounded array view (e.g., &[u8]).
        // Any attempt by a malformed packet to read/write past its length will safely panic.

        // 3. Hardware Cryptographic Authentication
        if PufHardware::verify_mesh_signature(frame_slice) {
            
            // 4. Zero-Copy FlatBuffer Overlay
            // Casts the validated byte slice directly into a strongly-typed payload struct
            // without allocating memory or copying bytes.
            if let Some(payload) = FlatBufferPayload::overlay(frame_slice) {
                return Ok(payload);
            }
        }
    }

    // Packet was malformed, unauthorized, or the buffer was empty.
    Err(BufferError::InvalidPayload)
}

#[panic_handler]
fn panic(_info: &PanicInfo) -> ! {
    // If a bounds-check fails (preventing an RCE), the node enters immediate physical survival mode
    ebony_hal::actuators::drop_powertrain_relays();
    loop {} // Halt execution to preserve physical and cryptographic integrity
}
